            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Dmitri Gallo is a product of an older, grittier San Francisco. Born and raised in the foggy avenues of the Outer Sunset, he is the son of an Italian-American fisherman and a second-generation Russian-American mother who worked as a seamstress. His upbringing was grounded in tangible skills and hard work, not academic theory. While his peers were being pushed toward college, Dmitri found his purpose in the controlled chaos of his high school metal shop, fascinated by the power to fuse and shape steel with fire and electricity.\n\nBypassing a traditional four-year degree, he earned a vocational certificate in welding from a local trade school. This decision set the course for his life. He honed his craft through apprenticeships, moving from simple structural welds to complex, artistic fabrications. Now a Master Welder, he operates out of a cavernous workshop in the Bayview-Hunters Point area, a holdout of the city\u2019s industrial past. He takes immense pride in his work, seeing himself not just as a tradesman but as a craftsman who builds the very bones of the city, from seismic retrofits to custom-designed architectural elements.\n\nA key turning point was a brief marriage in his early thirties, which dissolved under the immense financial pressure of the city and divergent life paths. The experience left him wary but self-reliant. Now single, Dmitri\u2019s social life revolves around a tight-knit crew of old friends\u2014a mechanic, a bartender, and a plumber\u2014who share his deep roots and quiet frustration with the new San Francisco. He lives in a rent-controlled apartment just blocks from his childhood home, a small but fiercely protected anchor to his past.\n\nHis daily routine is a ritual: a pre-dawn coffee, the 8.5-mile drive across the city in his aging pickup truck, passing gleaming tech campuses on his way to the sparks and grind of the workshop. Dmitri\u2019s connection to San Francisco is a complicated love affair. He cherishes the Pacific air and the city's rugged beauty but resents the transient, tech-fueled wealth that has pushed so many of his kind to the margins. His dream isn\u2019t a stock portfolio but a small, independent fabrication shop of his own\u2014a place to create and build on his own terms, ensuring the art of the welder endures in a city obsessed with the virtual."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was fifteen, standing in the noisy chaos of the high school metal shop. His teacher guided his hand to strike his first arc. A sudden, brilliant flash of blue-white light, brighter than the sun, and the acrid smell of ozone filled his senses. In that instant, he felt a power he\u2019d never known\u2014the ability to fuse steel, to create order from raw material. It wasn't just a skill; it was a language he finally understood. College felt irrelevant after that. This was real.\n\n2.\nJust before dawn, age thirteen, on his father\u2019s boat off the coast. The engine chugged, the air thick with salt and diesel. His father, smelling of bait and brine, pointed back at the waking city\u2014a silhouette against the pale sky. \"See that, Dima? It looks pretty, but it needs people with strong hands to hold it together.\" Dmitri saw the bridges, the docks, the bones of it all. It wasn't a postcard; it was a structure, a thing to be built and maintained.\n\n3.\nThe final argument wasn't loud. His ex-wife, her face illuminated by her laptop screen showing home listings in the East Bay, just sighed. \"Dmitri, your hands are always greasy. We can't build a *future* on a welder's salary *here*.\" The word \"here\" hung in the air. He looked at his calloused hands\u2014the source of his pride\u2014and realized they were speaking different languages about what a \"future\" even was. That conversation cemented the self-reliance he lives by now.\n\n4.\nA few years ago, after a minor quake rattled the Bay. He drove to a South of Market brick building he\u2019d spent six months retrofitting. From the street, it looked untouched. He ran his hand over a huge seismic brace he\u2019d welded into the facade, the steel cool and unyielding beneath his palm. Inside, people were working, oblivious. No one knew his name, but his welds were holding their world together. That quiet, anonymous contribution felt more valuable than any stock option.\n\n5.\nLast Tuesday, on his drive to Bayview, he saw it. The corner dive bar where his crew used to end their week was gone, replaced by a minimalist cafe with a neon sign that read \"Artisanal Elixirs.\" The familiar, beer-soaked darkness replaced by sterile white walls and chrome. He gripped the steering wheel of his old pickup, a cold anger settling in his gut. They weren't just taking the buildings; they were erasing the memories, one overpriced coffee at a time."
